The Monty Hall Problem

The Monty Hall Problem

The Lets Make a Deal game show (Image from wilsongrowthpartners.com)

The Monty Hall Problem is a brain teaser problem named after the host of Lets Make a Deal, an American game show on which it originated. In the show, contestants were asked to pick among three doors; whatevers behind it is for them to win. Behind one is a brand new car, while the remaining two doors each conceal a goat. After the contestants pick, Monty Hall would always open a door, revealing a goat behind it. The contestant is allowed to switch to the remaining unopened door. Should they do it? Lets try to answer that using probability.

Before we start, why not give it a try first? Click here to play the Monty Hall game.

Solving the Monty Hall Problem

At first glance, it seems as though no matter what door you pick youll only have a 1/3 chance of winning the car. Psychologically speaking, it will also hurt more to lose something we might think we had the chance of getting but not holding for it. It will be easier to admit that we just truly lost staying our ground than to lose and feel as if we missed our chance by not trusting ourselves. It might feel a bit counter intuitive, but probability says otherwise.

Indeed, at first, theres a 1/3 chance that the car is behind the door picked and a 2/3 chance that its behind one of the remaining doors. The key lies in the fact that the second door opened by the host will certainly have a goat behind it. That information collapses the 2/3 chance of the car being in either one of the doors to only the one remaining door.
knitr::include_graphics("https://brilliant-staff-media.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/tiffany-wang/gWotbuEdYC.png")
Image from Brilliant.org


This concept becomes more evident when we try to add more doors; say we have a hundred. When you pick a random door, there will be a 99/100 chance that the car will be behind another door and a 1 in 99 chance that it will be in the door you picked. When Monty Hall reveals the 98 doors that contain goats, leaving only the door you picked and another one, would you stay with your pick? Most likely than not, the car will be in the remaining unopened door as it now solely possesses a 99/100 chance of containing the car given the information about the other doors.

Another intuitive way to explain it is by listing all the possible outcomes and the most probable way to win. Initially, theres a 1/3 chance of picking the right door. If you picked it, the correct move is to stay. But theres a 2/3 chance that youll pick the wrong door, and the correct move will be to switch. Heres the list of all the correct moves (stay or switch) based on where the car is:


Door You Picked
Winning Door Door 1 Door 2 Door 3
Door 1 Stay Switch Switch
Door 2 Switch Stay Switch
Door 3 Switch Switch Stay
We can see here that the best move is to switch 6/9 or 2/3 of the time, therefore, the wiser choice is to take the switch.

Knowing this strategy doesnt mean youll always win, though. Theres still a 1/3 chance youll lose by using this strategy. But it not only increases your chances of winning; it also guarantees a win in the long run.You can play using the strategy with this website again.

Ultra Lotto Combinations

Forcing an Ultra Lotto Win

One of the most popular major games of PCSO is the Ultra Lotto 6/58. At 20 per ticket, how much would a bettor spend to cover all of the possible combinations. Would the grand prize of 50 million cover all the expenses or would it simply incur a massive loss on the bettor?
First, we need to find the number of possible combinations in Ultra Lotto 6/58. We should use combination since there are 58 choices and we only need to select 6, and the order of the numbers does not matter.

\(58C6 = 40,475,358\)

For Ultra Lotto 6/58, there are 40,475,358 possible combinations. Since 1 ticket equals 1 combination, and 1 ticket costs 20, the bettor would need to pay \(40,475,358 * 20 = 809,507,160\), to cover all combinations. The grand prize, though, is just 50 million, which is less than the amount the bettor would wager. Therefore, placing a bet on every single possible combination in the Ultra Lotto 6/58 will result in a huge loss (worth 759,507,160) for the bettor.


Still, it is obviously possible to win the 50 million without spending that much money, its just that the less you spend, the lower your chances. Nobody in their right mind would spend millions just for a small chance to win this lottery. Being something that isnt guaranteed or even likely, it just isnt worth it, no matter how much you spend. The way the lottery works is that it gets peoples hopes up by offering a large cash prize, which in reality is quite small compared to the amount of cash needed to actually win. This is why most of the winners are simply just extremely lucky, as they usually win at a large gain since they are somehow able to win with just a few combinations. With how probability works, no matter how small the chance, someone out there is still going to be able to win eventually.
